    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "EXPLICITLY FLAGGED LOW-CONFIDENCE INPUT — RED BLOOD CELL MECHANICAL DAMAGE THRESHOLD: The critical damage threshold stress (τ_c) for the Giersiepen-Wurzinger model is taken from Wurzinger et al. (1986) in-vitro data on bovine blood. This value carries a ±22% epistemic uncertainty (documented confidence score: LOW) because (a) the original dataset used bovine rather than human erythrocytes, (b) sample size was n=12, and (c) no independent replication study has been published with human blood under identical shear conditions. This gap is fully documented in the uncertainty budget and is the primary driver of the wide ±38% Monte Carlo prediction interval for hemolysis index. Despite this low-confidence input, the model predictions bracket all 5 experimental observations within the 90% CI, and the predicted nominal hemolysis index remains below the clinical threshold (NIH < 0.01 g/100 L) even at the upper bound of the uncertainty interval. All other model inputs (geometry, fluid viscosity, rotational speed, hematocrit) are characterized to Gradation 3 or better with narrow uncertainty bounds (< 8% each). The low-confidence τ_c input is accepted as residual epistemic uncertainty; its effect is fully captured in the reported prediction interval, and the regulatory decision accounts for this conservatively by evaluating compliance at the 90th percentile of the predicted HI distribution rather than the nominal value.",
